SIMPLE: wry
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wry
<hw>Wry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>wre⟦oacute⟧n</ets>.]</ety> <def>To cover.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Wrie</qex> you in that mantle.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wry
<hw>Wry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Wrier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Wriest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[Akin to OE. <ets>wrien</ets> to
twist, to bend, AS. <ets>wrigian</ets> to tend towards, to
drive.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Turned to one side; twisted; distorted; <as>as, a
<ex>wry</ex> mouth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, deviating from the right direction;
misdirected; out of place; <as>as, <ex>wry</ex> words</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not according to the <qex>wry</qex> rigor of our neighbors, who
never take up an old idea without some extravagance in its
application.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Wrested; perverted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . puts a <qex>wry</qex> sense upon Protestant writers.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wry face</b></col>, <cd>a distortion of the countenance
indicating impatience, disgust, or discomfort; a grimace.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wry
<hw>Wry</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To twist; to writhe; to
bend or wind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To deviate from the right way; to go away or astray;
to turn side; to swerve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This Phebus gan awayward for to <qex>wryen</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How many⟦br⟧
Must murder wives much better than themselves⟦br⟧
For <qex>wrying</qex> but a little!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Wry
<hw>Wry</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wried</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wrying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>wrien</ets>. See
<er>Wry</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To twist; to distort; to writhe;
to wrest; to vex.</def> <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Guests by hundreds, not one caring⟦br⟧
If the dear host's neck were <qex>wried</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>R.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrybill</ent>⟦br⟧
